Flexbox on the parent, three lines:

```css
.parent {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;  /* horizontal */
  align-items: center;      /* vertical */
}
```

That centers the child both ways inside whatever height the parent has — so for true vertical centering on the page, the parent needs an actual height to center within (e.g. `min-height: 100vh`), otherwise it'll only be as tall as its content and the vertical part will look like it did nothing.

If you only need to center a single block horizontally, the old reliable still works and needs no flex: give it a width and `margin: 0 auto`. And for one item in a container, `display: grid; place-items: center` does the same job in one declaration. Flexbox is the one to memorize — it covers the large majority of cases.
